'''Donbettyr''' ({{lang-os|Донбеттыр}}) is the [[List of water deities|god of all waters]], and the protector of [[fish]] and [[Fisherman|fishermen]] in [[Ossetian mythology]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=kD_dDQAAQBAJ&pg=PT148&lpg=PT148&dq=donbettyr&source=bl&ots=TVpcfhA1mm&sig=b4mgVI_zNIBd8UtN-XEgDZ2TQRM&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiDkoPC9szdAhXG8YMKHd13AXcQ6AEwC3oECAUQAQ#v=onepage&q=donbettyr&f=false|title=La Fée Mélusine : Le serpent et l'oiseau|last=Walter|first=Philippe|date=2008-01-01|publisher=Editions Imago|isbn=9782849524565|language=fr}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=cPHTAAAAMAAJ&q=donbettyr&dq=donbettyr&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi6leHx-czdAhUj2oMKHTi4Bg84ChDoAQhQMAc|title=The Origins of Russia|last=Vernadsky|first=George|date=1959|publisher=Clarendon Press|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=N_3UAAAAMAAJ&q=donbettyr&dq=donbettyr&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi6leHx-czdAhUj2oMKHTi4Bg84ChDoAQhaMAk|title=The Caucasus|date=1956|publisher=Language and Communication Research Center, Columbia University|language=en}}</ref> He is related to a [[Scythian mythology|Scythian]] deity of the same name.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=I7kLAQAAMAAJ&q=donbettyr&dq=donbettyr&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi6leHx-czdAhUj2oMKHTi4Bg84ChDoAQhUMAg|title=The Bronze Age and early Iron Age peoples of Eastern Central Asia|last=Peoples|first=International Conference on the Bronze Age and Iron Age|last2=Anthropology|first2=University of Pennsylvania University Museum of Archaeology and|date=May 1998|publisher=Institute for the Study of Man|year=|isbn=9780941694636|location=|pages=|language=en}}</ref> He is the Ossetian equivalent of the [[Greek mythology|Greek]] [[Poseidon]].<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=zxVmAAAAMAAJ&q=donbettyr&dq=donbettyr&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi5n__E9szdAhWr7oMKHbX4CboQ6AEIPDAE|title=The Indo-european and ancient Near Eastern sources of the Armenian epic: myth and history|last=Petrosyan|first=Armen|date=2002|publisher=Institute for the Study of Man|language=en}}</ref> His beautiful daughters are the Ossetian equivalent of [[Nereid|sea nymphs]].<ref name=":0" /> Through them, he is the ancestor of many of the heroes of the epic [[Nart saga]] of the north Caucasus, including [[Uryzmaeg]], [[Satanaya]], [[Xaemyts]], and [[Batraz]].<ref name=":1">{{Cite journal|last=Tuite|first=Kevin|date=1998|title=Achilles and the Caucasus|url=http://www.mapageweb.umontreal.ca/tuitekj/publications/Tuite_Achilles.pdf|journal=Journal of Indo-European Studies|volume=26|issue=3|pages=26-27|ref=harv|via=}}</ref>{{Sfn|Woodard|2013|p=217}}
== Relations == Donbettyr's golden-haired daughter [[Dzerassae]] was the mother of Uryzmaeg, Satanaya, and Xaemyts.<ref name=":1" />
Donbettyr is also the maternal grandfather of the Nart hero [[Batraz]], through the marriage of the hunter Xaemyts to an unnamed daughter of Donbettyr.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=EtV7BwAAQBAJ&pg=PA156&dq=donbettyr&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi5n__E9szdAhWr7oMKHbX4CboQ6AEIRDAG#v=onepage&q=donbettyr&f=false|title=Myth, Ritual, and the Warrior in Roman and Indo-European Antiquity|last=Woodard|first=Roger D.|date=2013-01-28|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=9781139851725|language=en}}</ref> In the story of their marriage, Xaemyts is chasing a white rabbit and shooting at it. It dies, but returns to life three times, before escaping to the coast where it dives into the sea. Donbettyr rises from the water and declares that the hare was actually his daughter and that Xaemyts must marry her.<ref name=":1"/> Xaemyts agrees, only to be told that his wife will appear on earth during the day in the form of a [[tortoise]]. Only at night will she take the form of the beautiful woman he married.<ref name=":1"/><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=eMhKAAAAYAAJ&q=donbettyr&dq=donbettyr&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi5n__E9szdAhWr7oMKHbX4CboQ6AEIODAD|title=Soviet Anthropology and Archeology|date=1985|publisher=International Arts and Sciences Press|language=en}}</ref>
When Uryzmaeg had a son, Donbettyr took it upon himself to raise the boy, deep beneath the sea.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=xXe4AQAAQBAJ&pg=PT145&dq=donbettyr&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi6leHx-czdAhUj2oMKHTi4Bg84ChDoAQgzMAI#v=onepage&q=donbettyr&f=false|title=From Scythia to Camelot: A Radical Reassessment of the Legends of King Arthur, the Knights of the Round Table, and the Holy Grail|last=Littleton|first=C. Scott|last2=Malcor|first2=Linda A.|date=2013-10-23|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781317777700|language=en}}</ref>
