[[File:Wooden honey dipper (5536641494).jpg|thumb|upright=1.35|A wooden honey dipper]]
A '''honey dipper''' is a [[kitchen utensil]] used to collect viscous liquid (generally [[honey]]) from a container, which it then exudes to another location. It is often made of [[Woodturning|turned wood]].<ref name="Woodworking">{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zQhJx6kr6mIC | title=The Wood Stash Project Book | publisher=Popular Woodworking Books | author=Pierce, Kerry | year=2002 | at=p. 41, Project 5: Two Honey Dippers  | isbn=1558706003}}</ref> Besides the handle, the tool consists of equally-spaced coaxial grooves.<ref name="VM">{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iEdwfFlnCMYC | title=Visual Marketing | publisher=John Wiley and Sons Inc. | year=2011 | at=46. New Beverage Design Creates Buzz- Why It Works | isbn=9781118035672 | first1=David | last1=Langton | first2=Anita | last2=Cambell}}</ref> 

One method of using the tool is to dip the grooved end into the liquid, then slowly twirl the handle between the thumb and fingers while in transport, to prevent dripping.<ref name="Method">{{cite news | url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1683&dat=20050607&id=TroaAAAAIBAJ&sjid=YUUEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6616,5568418&hl=en | title=Gadget quiz answers | work=Journal Sentinel | date=June 7, 2005 | agency=Journal Sentinel Inc. | accessdate=November 16, 2015 | author=Berger, J.A. | at=pp. 9,12 First-Time Home Buyers}}</ref> It is  commonly used to drizzle honey on bread, biscuits, or other foods of that nature.<ref name="SHT">{{cite news | url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1755&dat=19991208&id=HiEcAAAAIBAJ&sjid=MH4EAAAAIBAJ&pg=3255,3185804&hl=en | title=Cook's Toys | work=Sarasota Herald-Tribune | date=December 8, 1999 | accessdate=November 16, 2015 | author=Underwood, Hillary | at=p. E1 Cuisine}}</ref> The tool is sometimes made of plastic<ref name=SHT /> or glass.

