== Alternative term usage ==
Since the 1920s, the term "honey dipper" has been used as a [[term of disparagement]] for the workers who empty [[septic tanks]], clean [[latrines]], and do similar work.<ref name="Cassel/NPD">
Sources for the alternative slang meaning of "honey dipper":
*{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5GpLcC4a5fAC | title=Cassell's Dictionary of Slang | publisher=Weidenfeld and Nicolson | author=Green, Jonathan | year=2005 | at=p. 732, honey·dipper | isbn=0304366366 | edition=Second}}
*{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bbcBCgAAQBAJ | title=The New Partridge Dictionary of Slang and Unconventional English | publisher=Routledge | year=2013 | at=p. 1169, honey dipper | isbn=9780415619493 | edition=Second | first1=Tom | last1=Dalzell | first2=Terry | last2=Vicotor}}</ref> There are many other terms for people doing this work; see [[Manual_scavenging#History|the history of manual scavenging]] and [[History of water supply and sanitation|the history of sanitation]].

